PiperOrigin-RevId: 395251678
Change-Id: I42c37110919dee919f303f2bd818066617468e36","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/tensorflow/tensorflow/commits/861eefd9e575f7a990002058cff9899aa078fcbe"},{"sha":"469a051e0ebe21d647905390111a7ca593a2a906","author":{"name":"Justin Lebar","email":"631d11d9fe908fc8f04b5865032c3043cb48fdfb@google.com"},"message":"Skip get-tuple-element nodes in graphviz.

Re-land cl/394286090, which was rolled back in cl/394760138 due to
CHECK-failures.

The only difference between this and the original is inside GetNodeForEdge.  In
the original, we unnested fusions first, then unnested GTEs.  Now we reverse
the order; first we unnest GTEs, then we unnest fusions.  This is necessary to
avoid crashes when rendering multi-output-fusions.

The tuple index is written inside the consuming instruction as e.g.  "operand 1
= tuple-element 3 of fusion.42".

Alternative considered: My first attempt was to put the tuple element in the
edge label, which right now contains the operand index.  This didn't work well.
Graphviz doesn't prevent the edge label from overlapping with the edge itself
or anything else in the graph.  It was irredeemably messy.

functions from the Istio submodule. Break the circular dependency by

fiber reconciler. It's mostly a copy-paste of the userspace
implementation, which is not ideal but is a good enough starting place.

move the tearing checks from the layout phase to an earlier, pre-commit
phase so that code that runs in the commit phase always observes a
consistent tree.

- Implement in react-debug-hooks","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/woutheijnen/react/commits/06f98c168060ef0213526a1aee696a568cec7f54"},{"sha":"8e80592a3ab2bdbd036f5af77c89fcf937b8f43b","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Remove state queue from useSyncExternalStore (#22265)

The userspace shim of useSyncExternalStore uses a useState hook because
it's the only way to trigger a re-render. We don't actually use the
queue to store anything, because we read the current value directly
from the store.

Add support for binding TrafficRoute resources to Gateways. This is
based on outbound proxy generator code, but there are still a number of
missing features and outstanding TODO items.

It is possible to configure simple HTTP Gateway use cases and forward
traffic to Kuma services as long as the mesh is not configures with mTLS.
A Gateway can have more than one TrafficRoute resource bound, and this
works correctly by merging the routes in match order.

The Istio submodule imports Kuma config definitions, and Kuma calls
functions from the Istio submodule. Break the circular dependency by
moving the config definitions into the Istio submodule, even though
they more properly belong in Kuma itself.

This makes it possible to run `go mod tidy` in the Istio submodule.

This fixes #2087.

[{"sha":"fa4f1bdb04f1e94f6b55186d84ee43c511c5c203","author":{"name":"Charly Molter","email":"0bf65b3a46647433ba986e4a2e1eee2b81710fbd@konghq.com"},"message":"fix(kds): Avoid calling `Send()` from different goroutines (#2573)

Rewrote most of KDS mux as it wasn't working as intended.
KDS mux now ensures:

Recv() on underlying streams are always called in the same goroutine
Send() on underlying streams are always called in the same goroutine
Close() actually waits for some goroutine to terminate
Also added extra tests to ensure these invariants

Fixes #2492

Signed-off-by: Jakub Dyszkiewicz <jakub.dyszkiewicz@gmail.com>","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/rizalgowandy/kuma/commits/c77077d75dfd651b586da2accd9bc30f81c7ad14"},{"sha":"d5af0df5ec5551fd40bdc5309827dce0d6e20588","author":{"name":"James Peach","email":"cfb385863e43a54966ce6ee8158f84aabd7009b9@konghq.com"},"message":"feat(kuma-cp) initial gateway TrafficRoute support (#2547)

Add support for binding TrafficRoute resources to Gateways. This is
based on outbound proxy generator code, but there are still a number of
missing features and outstanding TODO items.

It is possible to configure simple HTTP Gateway use cases and forward
traffic to Kuma services as long as the mesh is not configures with mTLS.
A Gateway can have more than one TrafficRoute resource bound, and this
works correctly by merging the routes in match order.

Signed-off-by: James Peach <james.peach@konghq.com>","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/rizalgowandy/kuma/commits/d5af0df5ec5551fd40bdc5309827dce0d6e20588"},{"sha":"6f2b6210e8ef9fcbe916c73e0950890d161316db","author":{"name":"James Peach","email":"cfb385863e43a54966ce6ee8158f84aabd7009b9@konghq.com"},"message":"fix(*) remove circular dependency on the Istio submodule (#2742)

The Istio submodule imports Kuma config definitions, and Kuma calls
functions from the Istio submodule. Break the circular dependency by
moving the config definitions into the Istio submodule, even though
they more properly belong in Kuma itself.

This makes it possible to run `go mod tidy` in the Istio submodule.

This fixes #2087.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 395346910
Change-Id: I2179baa5f5393a06dcd9aa2be56f263e344a8bdd","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/greedisgoood/tensorflow/commits/cf0d51e649cb9e1a41a437dc41f8a1982bb698e3"},{"sha":"5a24a36d748c97ac4df6be8b79f8c7cb8faf60be","author":{"name":"Andrew Audibert","email":"23f2b5dd93c922fa4b806faa35ad0644038a966e@google.com"},"message":"[tf.data service] Centralize default server values.

Previously, we specified the default values for parameters such as "job_gc_timeout_ms" in multiple places. These could easily get out of sync, and make it hard to evolve the default behavior. Additionally, the default protocol buffer configuration value is 0, but this doesn't match the logical default value.

To solve these issues, this CL updates the meaning of `0` to mean "Leave the default up to the runtime". Then we only need to set the default in one place: in the implementation. This has the added benefit that the default protocol buffer values match the default behavior we want.

Change-Id: Ic0e87bedb95893301da37191fc101fbc279e22ef","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/GesuPlace/tensorflow/commits/32f82e53099483da528987dd917392bd66c1770f"},{"sha":"86b1d613792d33f7c0d296ff84b11a3dad20faab","author":{"name":"Andrew Audibert","email":"23f2b5dd93c922fa4b806faa35ad0644038a966e@google.com"},"message":"[MLIR][KernelGen] Fix GPU module cache and make it a kernel resource

This fixes a subtle bug in the GPU module caches, which assumed that no two GPU
modules are loaded from the same memory location. When JIT-compiling kernels,
however, this can (and did) happen, which previously lead to a false cache hit,
resulting in the use of an incorrect GPU kernel.

Making the GPU module cache a kernel resource binds its lifetime to that of the
kernel context and also to that of the JIT cache....

PiperOrigin-RevId: 395122045
Change-Id: I4ddd93c57c09736eada8ee24c198c8399cc6f969","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/athulcoder/tensorflow/commits/1d022ce477f717dbf37f2f85a387fb4996f40d82"},{"sha":"860058301de30b6feedeb890f54f5475d26d82c7","author":{"name":"Alexander Belyaev","email":"a33a2701f6790f0a44360bcc1a194138e928e0d3@google.com"},"message":"[KERNEL_GEN] Add a separate bufferization pass for linalg.tiled_loop.

TiledLoopOp is generated only when a Linalg compute operation (linalg.generic,
linalg.dot, etc) is tiled. Due to a special structure of the resulting loop
nest we can make some assumptions about the operations in its body. For
example, that we don't have to allocate buffers for the `tensor.extract_slice`
if the source tensor is the block arg of the enclosing `linalg.tiled_loop`.

Bufferization of `tensor.insert_slice` inside of the tiled_loop also differs
from the conservative bufferization in the general case.

With the new pass we can still use bufferization patterns for LinalgOps from
MLIR Core for operations that are not in the body of the tiled_loop and use
custom bufferization patterns otherwise.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 395149103
Change-Id: Ia2a5670ea75a19065d8b5b62dbc13fa9a9115063","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/athulcoder/tensorflow/commits/34aa96a20e195c2f8a82ff62bd788cb3d5d13a75"},{"sha":"034300c177d6bd9dead29a1366fb37944a0c07f5","author":{"name":"Thai Nguyen","email":"77c7cb715bbfb6a72d1c8dd380160fd6eb2ba9c0@google.com"},"message":"Support UniformQuantizedPerAxisType element type in TFL_TransposeOp

Current Build and Verify methods of the TransposeOp assumes that the quantized axes of input and output are the same. However, the quantized axis changes after transposing.

This cl adds a method named "RequiredSameQuantizedAxes" to the SameOperandsAndResultsScale interface. Other ops like BatchToSpaceNdOp, SpaceToBatchNdOp,... or ReshapeOp can use this method to disable the check for quantized axes when there is a need to support UniformQuantizedPerAxisType in these ops.

The issue was found when transposing the filter of TFL_Conv2dOp to match the filter input of TF_Conv2DOp.

Change-Id: I2179baa5f5393a06dcd9aa2be56f263e344a8bdd","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/UofT-EcoSystem/tensorflow/commits/cf0d51e649cb9e1a41a437dc41f8a1982bb698e3"},{"sha":"5a24a36d748c97ac4df6be8b79f8c7cb8faf60be","author":{"name":"Andrew Audibert","email":"23f2b5dd93c922fa4b806faa35ad0644038a966e@google.com"},"message":"[tf.data service] Centralize default server values.

Previously, we specified the default values for parameters such as "job_gc_timeout_ms" in multiple places. These could easily get out of sync, and make it hard to evolve the default behavior. Additionally, the default protocol buffer configuration value is 0, but this doesn't match the logical default value.

To solve these issues, this CL updates the meaning of `0` to mean "Leave the default up to the runtime". Then we only need to set the default in one place: in the implementation. This has the added benefit that the default protocol buffer values match the default behavior we want.

* fix(dns): Ensure outbounds are set when migrating from old to new

There's a bug when migrating from one version to the other.
This is caused by the fact that we don't set OutboundEntry when
migrating from old to new format.

This patch:

- Adds validation on VirtualOutboundView to avoid this in the future
- Adds an OutboundEntry for Services with a single tag
- Adds an OutboundEntry for ExternalServices by fetching back the original
virtual service to retrieve its serviceName

Signed-off-by: Charly Molter <charly.molter@konghq.com>","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/rizalgowandy/kuma/commits/203c0725665b5b6f1f7edbf31a8c57e291eff25b"},{"sha":"15df736ff07cf044c89baec485b410d6dc2961fc","author":{"name":"Charly Molter","email":"0bf65b3a46647433ba986e4a2e1eee2b81710fbd@konghq.com"},"message":"fix(proxy-template): Correct bad merging of duration (#2700)

We used to merge 10s and 0.5s into 10.5s this is because
proto.Duration is made of 2 fields (seconds and nanos) and the default
merge method would just add these 2 fields separately.

This patch copies the content of proto.Merge but enables us
to override the merge policy for specific types.

This commit adds the `--concurrency` flag to kuma-dp, which is propagated
to Envoy's `--concurrency` flag. On Linux, if there is no explicit
concurrency, we pass `--cpuset-threads` so that Envoy will automatically
scale its worker thread if it is in a cpuset.

In Kubernetes clusters, we can add additional automatic controls for the
Envoy concurrency. We know the amount of CPU resource reserved for the
proxy container, so we can tune that automatically. If the operator knows
better, then can set an explicit concurency value with a pod annotation.

This fixes #1721.

Plumbs device IDs for the physical devices through to collectives.

For TPUs these come from the topology at initialization time, and are only available for locally attached devices. Adds the global ID to DeviceAttributes so it is exchanged when preparing for collectives.

[{"sha":"6f2b6210e8ef9fcbe916c73e0950890d161316db","author":{"name":"James Peach","email":"cfb385863e43a54966ce6ee8158f84aabd7009b9@konghq.com"},"message":"fix(*) remove circular dependency on the Istio submodule (#2742)

The Istio submodule imports Kuma config definitions, and Kuma calls
functions from the Istio submodule. Break the circular dependency by
moving the config definitions into the Istio submodule, even though
they more properly belong in Kuma itself.

This makes it possible to run `go mod tidy` in the Istio submodule.

This fixes #2087.

Add support for binding TrafficRoute resources to Gateways. This is
based on outbound proxy generator code, but there are still a number of
missing features and outstanding TODO items.

It is possible to configure simple HTTP Gateway use cases and forward
traffic to Kuma services as long as the mesh is not configures with mTLS.
A Gateway can have more than one TrafficRoute resource bound, and this
works correctly by merging the routes in match order.

* fix(dns): Ensure outbounds are set when migrating from old to new

There's a bug when migrating from one version to the other.
This is caused by the fact that we don't set OutboundEntry when
migrating from old to new format.

This patch:

- Adds validation on VirtualOutboundView to avoid this in the future
- Adds an OutboundEntry for Services with a single tag
- Adds an OutboundEntry for ExternalServices by fetching back the original
virtual service to retrieve its serviceName

Signed-off-by: Charly Molter <charly.molter@konghq.com>","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/kumahq/kuma/commits/203c0725665b5b6f1f7edbf31a8c57e291eff25b"},{"sha":"15df736ff07cf044c89baec485b410d6dc2961fc","author":{"name":"Charly Molter","email":"0bf65b3a46647433ba986e4a2e1eee2b81710fbd@konghq.com"},"message":"fix(proxy-template): Correct bad merging of duration (#2700)

We used to merge 10s and 0.5s into 10.5s this is because
proto.Duration is made of 2 fields (seconds and nanos) and the default
merge method would just add these 2 fields separately.

This patch copies the content of proto.Merge but enables us
to override the merge policy for specific types.

[{"sha":"a43f1c5e4dc3bd2955df13c844d0d7a6e8eac628","author":{"name":"Reed Wanderman-Milne","email":"75734eae9db3e4fb4d6c671d22722b468d1a389b@google.com"},"message":"When determinism is enabled, raise error in tf.timestamp.

A FailedPrecondition error is raised. InvalidArgument is used for random ops when the seed isn't specified, but that doesn't apply here as there are no arguments.

tf.timestamp is mostly used to seed random ops. It is also occasionally used for measuring the performance of some part of the model. The latter case is a legitimate use case when determinism is used, but we must raise an error to guard against the former case.

This fixes a subtle bug in the GPU module caches, which assumed that no two GPU
modules are loaded from the same memory location. When JIT-compiling kernels,
however, this can (and did) happen, which previously lead to a false cache hit,
resulting in the use of an incorrect GPU kernel.

Making the GPU module cache a kernel resource binds its lifetime to that of the
kernel context and also to that of the JIT cache....

Change-Id: Ieb4f1ae11da0913da4e0fb304da7521e521c5e26","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/mnpoonia/phoenix/commits/3a4339e83c5aa28826c8402ef39e61e27c257c6c"},{"sha":"152c157e1bce85dccface13f95586f7e4f51eb6f","author":{"name":"Bharath Vissapragada","email":"f23dbca75acdac4082d6a05c290fc03565dada86@apache.org"},"message":"PHOENIX-5543: Implement SHOW TABLES/SCHEMAS sql commands

This patch adds new SQL grammar like following

- SHOW SCHEMAS [like '<pattern>']
- SHOW TABLES [IN <schema>] [like '<pattern']

Example invocations:

- show schemas
- show scemas like 'SYS%'
- show tables
- show tables in SYSTEM
- show tables in SYSTEM like 'CAT%'

The current way of fetching this information is by using
!tables and !schemas via sqlline JDBC support but that is
not flexible enough for the end users to add more fitlers.
This approach is more inline with what other databases do.

Added test coverage in parser tests and core e2e tests.

Change-Id: Ic0e87bedb95893301da37191fc101fbc279e22ef","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/greedisgoood/tensorflow/commits/32f82e53099483da528987dd917392bd66c1770f"},{"sha":"86b1d613792d33f7c0d296ff84b11a3dad20faab","author":{"name":"Andrew Audibert","email":"23f2b5dd93c922fa4b806faa35ad0644038a966e@google.com"},"message":"[MLIR][KernelGen] Fix GPU module cache and make it a kernel resource

This fixes a subtle bug in the GPU module caches, which assumed that no two GPU
modules are loaded from the same memory location. When JIT-compiling kernels,
however, this can (and did) happen, which previously lead to a false cache hit,
resulting in the use of an incorrect GPU kernel.

Making the GPU module cache a kernel resource binds its lifetime to that of the
kernel context and also to that of the JIT cache....

PiperOrigin-RevId: 395537793
Change-Id: I9ea999e4a23ce5c63d392d8605029f322d664c45","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/greedisgoood/tensorflow/commits/a1d58a9f50c594b311c0998429d25d3cc5e392e5"},{"sha":"5e4adb9583a5b1652e33c18ce73c16cfbdab958f","author":{"name":"Reed Wanderman-Milne","email":"75734eae9db3e4fb4d6c671d22722b468d1a389b@google.com"},"message":"Rewrite ParallelMapDataset in make_deterministic.

This makes calling Dataset.map deterministic when stateful ops are in the map_fn (assuming the user doesn't pass deterministic=False to map or tf.data.Options).

Unfortunately, this can make a model's input pipeline very very slow when determinism is enabled. For example, on the official resnet50 model with 8 V100s, performance drops from 5199 images/sec to 331 images/sec, making performance only 6% of what it is without determinism. The input pipeline is probably even slower than 6% of it's original speed, as the model is bottlenecked by the GPU without determinism and by the input pipeline with determinism. In the future, I hope to improve performance when determinism is enabled.

[{"sha":"86b1d613792d33f7c0d296ff84b11a3dad20faab","author":{"name":"Andrew Audibert","email":"23f2b5dd93c922fa4b806faa35ad0644038a966e@google.com"},"message":"[MLIR][KernelGen] Fix GPU module cache and make it a kernel resource

This fixes a subtle bug in the GPU module caches, which assumed that no two GPU
modules are loaded from the same memory location. When JIT-compiling kernels,
however, this can (and did) happen, which previously lead to a false cache hit,
resulting in the use of an incorrect GPU kernel.

Making the GPU module cache a kernel resource binds its lifetime to that of the
kernel context and also to that of the JIT cache....

PiperOrigin-RevId: 395346910
Change-Id: I2179baa5f5393a06dcd9aa2be56f263e344a8bdd","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/GesuPlace/tensorflow/commits/cf0d51e649cb9e1a41a437dc41f8a1982bb698e3"},{"sha":"5a24a36d748c97ac4df6be8b79f8c7cb8faf60be","author":{"name":"Andrew Audibert","email":"23f2b5dd93c922fa4b806faa35ad0644038a966e@google.com"},"message":"[tf.data service] Centralize default server values.

Previously, we specified the default values for parameters such as "job_gc_timeout_ms" in multiple places. These could easily get out of sync, and make it hard to evolve the default behavior. Additionally, the default protocol buffer configuration value is 0, but this doesn't match the logical default value.

To solve these issues, this CL updates the meaning of `0` to mean "Leave the default up to the runtime". Then we only need to set the default in one place: in the implementation. This has the added benefit that the default protocol buffer values match the default behavior we want.

[{"sha":"64387f4e027a4e4980a4203cf78a87c3c402c659","author":{"name":"Austin Anderson","email":"3151abf3c4c3b9378c98ede6ff5f755099ce0bdc@google.com"},"message":"Fix buggy original implementation of the sizetracker git version workaround

My original version of this fix last week was a bit buggy; I forgot that the
git_pretty function can be given a range of commits, and that the CL would be
different for each result. This new fix is much simpler, and does not act
differently for different versions of git, so I'm not going to miss it again.

The data is still correct, but results with the original fix do not correctly
include a full range of CLs, and they instead repeat the same one many times.

[{"sha":"6f2b6210e8ef9fcbe916c73e0950890d161316db","author":{"name":"James Peach","email":"cfb385863e43a54966ce6ee8158f84aabd7009b9@konghq.com"},"message":"fix(*) remove circular dependency on the Istio submodule (#2742)

The Istio submodule imports Kuma config definitions, and Kuma calls
functions from the Istio submodule. Break the circular dependency by
moving the config definitions into the Istio submodule, even though
they more properly belong in Kuma itself.

This makes it possible to run `go mod tidy` in the Istio submodule.

This fixes #2087.

Signed-off-by: James Peach <james.peach@konghq.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/jpeach/kuma/commits/6f2b6210e8ef9fcbe916c73e0950890d161316db"},{"sha":"4ff26a330abb1e6d4a3937f1e9ff281d04f32b17","author":{"name":"James Peach","email":"cfb385863e43a54966ce6ee8158f84aabd7009b9@konghq.com"},"message":"fix(*) switch Gateway to a selectors field

A Gateway matches a dataplane directly; it doesn't match a traffic flow.
This means that a `selectors` field is more direct and consistent with
the Kuma API than a `sources` field.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 395508116
Change-Id: Ic0e87bedb95893301da37191fc101fbc279e22ef","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/sloppyjuicy/tensorflow/commits/32f82e53099483da528987dd917392bd66c1770f"},{"sha":"86b1d613792d33f7c0d296ff84b11a3dad20faab","author":{"name":"Andrew Audibert","email":"23f2b5dd93c922fa4b806faa35ad0644038a966e@google.com"},"message":"[MLIR][KernelGen] Fix GPU module cache and make it a kernel resource

This fixes a subtle bug in the GPU module caches, which assumed that no two GPU
modules are loaded from the same memory location. When JIT-compiling kernels,
however, this can (and did) happen, which previously lead to a false cache hit,
resulting in the use of an incorrect GPU kernel.

Making the GPU module cache a kernel resource binds its lifetime to that of the
kernel context and also to that of the JIT cache....

Change-Id: Ia8fe5aad4d6d1f95b157ec35b110dba6242d709d","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/sloppyjuicy/tensorflow/commits/6cfb888ddd2fe9ca93f1fc63cbdd30dffa6b2627"},{"sha":"a43f1c5e4dc3bd2955df13c844d0d7a6e8eac628","author":{"name":"Reed Wanderman-Milne","email":"75734eae9db3e4fb4d6c671d22722b468d1a389b@google.com"},"message":"When determinism is enabled, raise error in tf.timestamp.

A FailedPrecondition error is raised. InvalidArgument is used for random ops when the seed isn't specified, but that doesn't apply here as there are no arguments.

tf.timestamp is mostly used to seed random ops. It is also occasionally used for measuring the performance of some part of the model. The latter case is a legitimate use case when determinism is used, but we must raise an error to guard against the former case.

Change-Id: Ia8fe5aad4d6d1f95b157ec35b110dba6242d709d","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/UofT-EcoSystem/tensorflow/commits/6cfb888ddd2fe9ca93f1fc63cbdd30dffa6b2627"},{"sha":"a43f1c5e4dc3bd2955df13c844d0d7a6e8eac628","author":{"name":"Reed Wanderman-Milne","email":"75734eae9db3e4fb4d6c671d22722b468d1a389b@google.com"},"message":"When determinism is enabled, raise error in tf.timestamp.

A FailedPrecondition error is raised. InvalidArgument is used for random ops when the seed isn't specified, but that doesn't apply here as there are no arguments.

tf.timestamp is mostly used to seed random ops. It is also occasionally used for measuring the performance of some part of the model. The latter case is a legitimate use case when determinism is used, but we must raise an error to guard against the former case.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 395251678
Change-Id: I42c37110919dee919f303f2bd818066617468e36","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/mahak/tensorflow/commits/861eefd9e575f7a990002058cff9899aa078fcbe"},{"sha":"469a051e0ebe21d647905390111a7ca593a2a906","author":{"name":"Justin Lebar","email":"631d11d9fe908fc8f04b5865032c3043cb48fdfb@google.com"},"message":"Skip get-tuple-element nodes in graphviz.

Re-land cl/394286090, which was rolled back in cl/394760138 due to
CHECK-failures.

The only difference between this and the original is inside GetNodeForEdge.  In
the original, we unnested fusions first, then unnested GTEs.  Now we reverse
the order; first we unnest GTEs, then we unnest fusions.  This is necessary to
avoid crashes when rendering multi-output-fusions.

The tuple index is written inside the consuming instruction as e.g.  "operand 1
= tuple-element 3 of fusion.42".

Alternative considered: My first attempt was to put the tuple element in the
edge label, which right now contains the operand index.  This didn't work well.
Graphviz doesn't prevent the edge label from overlapping with the edge itself
or anything else in the graph.  It was irredeemably messy.

move the tearing checks from the layout phase to an earlier, pre-commit

[{"sha":"5e4adb9583a5b1652e33c18ce73c16cfbdab958f","author":{"name":"Reed Wanderman-Milne","email":"75734eae9db3e4fb4d6c671d22722b468d1a389b@google.com"},"message":"Rewrite ParallelMapDataset in make_deterministic.

This makes calling Dataset.map deterministic when stateful ops are in the map_fn (assuming the user doesn't pass deterministic=False to map or tf.data.Options).

Unfortunately, this can make a model's input pipeline very very slow when determinism is enabled. For example, on the official resnet50 model with 8 V100s, performance drops from 5199 images/sec to 331 images/sec, making performance only 6% of what it is without determinism. The input pipeline is probably even slower than 6% of it's original speed, as the model is bottlenecked by the GPU without determinism and by the input pipeline with determinism. In the future, I hope to improve performance when determinism is enabled.
